  "text": "TLS configuration flows through the Prometheus ecosystem from high-level configuration to the actual crypto/tls.Config used in HTTP clients. The chain begins in prometheus/prometheus/config/config.go where ScrapeConfig, RemoteWriteConfig, RemoteReadConfig, and AlertmanagerConfig each embed an HTTPClientConfig field containing TLSConfig. HTTPClientConfig and TLSConfig are defined in prometheus/common/config/http_config.go (lines 332 and 1199 respectively).\n\nThe TLSConfig struct holds certificate paths (ca_file, cert_file, key_file), inline certificates (ca, cert, key), secret manager references (ca_ref, cert_ref, key_ref), server name, and TLS version constraints (MinVersion, MaxVersion). It includes validation via the Validate() method (line 1253) and YAML unmarshaling (line 1242). The SetDirectory() method (line 1232) handles relative path resolution.\n\nWhen creating HTTP clients for scraping, prometheus/prometheus/scrape/scrape.go:newScrapeClient() (line 2260) calls config_util.NewClientFromConfig(). For remote write, prometheus/prometheus/storage/remote/client.go:NewWriteClient() (line 183) and NewReadClient() (line 151) also use NewClientFromConfig().\n\nNewClientFromConfig() (line 605 in http_config.go) delegates to NewRoundTripperFromConfig(), which calls NewRoundTripperFromConfigWithContext() (line 629). This function creates the actual http.Transport with the TLS configuration. At line 739, it calls opts.newTLSConfigFunc(ctx, &cfg.TLSConfig, ...), which defaults to NewTLSConfigWithContext().\n\nNewTLSConfigWithContext() (line 1138) performs the critical transformation from the YAML/config TLSConfig to the actual crypto/tls.Config. It validates the configuration (line 1144), creates a base tls.Config with InsecureSkipVerify, MinVersion, and MaxVersion (lines 1148-1152), loads the CA certificate by calling updateRootCA() (line 1171), sets ServerName (line 1177), and configures client certificate callbacks via GetClientCertificate (lines 1186-1192). The getClientCertificate() method (line 1302) loads certificates from files, inline values, or secret manager references, creating a tls.X509KeyPair.\n\nIf TLS certificate files are mutable (detected by roundTripperSettings.immutable() at line 1749), NewTLSRoundTripperWithContext() wraps the round tripper to enable automatic reloading of certificates. The tlsRoundTripper (line 1350) watches file hashes and reconstructs the tls.Config when certificates change.\n\nThe final crypto/tls.Config is placed into http.Transport.TLSClientConfig (line 657) where it controls TLS handshaking for scrape and remote-write HTTP connections. Both scrape targets and remote storage backends (read/write) flow through this same configuration and client creation pipeline. Certificate validation, client authentication, and TLS version enforcement all occur through this unified mechanism."
